Application is designed using Event Sourcing and CQRS patterns.
MongoDB is used both as Event Store and for read projections.
Architecture allows easy extraction into independent microservices.

# Transactions Import API

A Spring Boot application for importing bank account transactions and generating aggregated statistics.
The system is designed using Event Sourcing and CQRS patterns and is ready to be evolved into a
fully distributed microservices architecture.

# Architecture Overview

The application follows Event Sourcing as the core domain pattern:

- All state changes are represented as immutable domain events
- MongoDB is used as:
  - Event Store (source of truth)
  - Read model storage (projections)
- Command and Query responsibilities are clearly separated (CQRS)

Although currently implemented as a single application, the internal structure allows
easy extraction into independent microservices.

# High-level Flow
CSV File Upload
|
v
Command API (Import)
|
v
Domain Aggregate (ImportAggregate)
|
v
Domain Events
|
v
Event Store (MongoDB)
|
v
Event Handlers
|
v
Read Projections (MongoDB)
|
v
Query API (Statistics & Status)

#Core Concepts

Import Aggregate
---------------------------------
Represents a single CSV import process.
It validates input data and emits domain events such as:

- ImportStarted
- TransactionImported
- TransactionRejected
- ImportCompleted

Event Store
---------------------------------
All domain events are persisted in MongoDB.
Events are immutable and ordered per aggregate.

Projections (Read Models)
---------------------------------
Dedicated MongoDB collections optimized for queries:
- Statistics by category
- Statistics by IBAN
- Statistics by month
- Import status

#API

Command API
- `POST /api/imports` – start new import
- `POST /api/imports/{id}/file` – upload CSV file

Query API
- `GET /api/imports/{id}/status`
- `GET /api/stats/category`
- `GET /api/stats/iban`
- `GET /api/stats/month`

#CSV Format

Each row in the CSV file must contain:
IBAN,transactionDate,currency,category,amount
Example: DE89370400440532013000,2026-01-15,EUR,GROCERIES,120.50

#Running the Application

Prerequisites
- Java 17+
- Docker & Docker Compose

Start infrastructure
```bash
docker compose up -d

Start application
./gradlew bootRun

Application will be available at:
http://localhost:8080

Health Check
GET /actuator/health

Basic workflow:
Start process:
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/imports
Return id, e.g. c9904a32-fe08-4dd1-91f1-960968b0afc7

Upload file:
curl -X POST -F "file=@data/transactions.csv" http://localhost:8080/api/imports/c9904a32-fe08-4dd1-91f1-960968b0afc7/file

Check file upload status:
curl http://localhost:8080/api/imports/c9904a32-fe08-4dd1-91f1-960968b0afc7/status

Check statistics:
curl.exe http://localhost:8080/api/stats/category
curl.exe http://localhost:8080/api/stats/iban
curl.exe http://localhost:8080/api/stats/month

Docker e.g. commands
docker exec -it transactions-mongo mongosh
show dbs
use transactions
show collections

Future Improvements
1. Asynchronous event processing (Kafka / RabbitMQ)
2. Snapshotting for faster aggregate rebuild
3. Authentication & authorization
4. Separate deployment per microservice
